Estimation of seatrout weight in Karup Ã…

Lars Relund Nielsen

19/3/2020

We consider catch records from Karup Ã… in years 2003-2020 with both weight and length numbers. A total of 15669 observations.

Model 1: log(Weight) ~ log(Length)

Let us first try a simple model with weight as function of length:

#> 
#> Call:
#> lm(formula = log(Weight) ~ log(Length), data = dat)
#> 
#> Residuals:
#>      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
#> -1.13766 -0.05952  0.02138  0.07404  0.72500 
#> 
#> Coefficients:
#>               Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
#> (Intercept) -11.546816   0.021308  -541.9   <2e-16 ***
#> log(Length)   3.043549   0.005214   583.7   <2e-16 ***
#> ---
#> Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
#> 
#> Residual standard error: 0.1307 on 15667 degrees of freedom
#> Multiple R-squared:  0.956,  Adjusted R-squared:  0.956 
#> F-statistic: 3.407e+05 on 1 and 15667 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

The estimated formula for weight (\(w\)) of a seatrout as a funtion of length (\(l\)) becomes:

\[ v = 9.67\times 10^{-6} \cdot l^{3.04}\]

Estimates with 95% confidence intervals are:

Note that the condition factor for average weight value is quite constanct ([1.14,1.18]) and increasing with lenght. Moreover, the weights in the plot of the first quarter (Q1) seem to be lower. This holds with the biology of the trout. In March the may still be kelts in the river.

Model 2: lm(log(Weight) ~ Month*log(Length)

Let us have a closer look at the data:

For medium lengths, weight goes up, peak and goes down again as expected. In March/April we still have kelts in the river and then fresh fish arrives (best condition/weight) which loose weight at they stay in the river. Note for small lengths (up to 50 cm) the difference is small; because, small fish may have other reasons than spawning for staying in the river (e.g.Â feeding or bad conditions in the fjord).

Model 4 provides a better fit compared to Model 2. I guess this is mainly due to the number of explanable variables in much lower (Df = -12). However, not all seatrouts arrive on April, but also May, June etc. We may try to join some months.

Reducing Months

Since the trout may arrive to the river in different months, we may try to group some of the months. We test different models both with month as numeric and factor.

dat <- dat %>% 
  mutate(MonthM5 = case_when(
    Month == "apr" ~ 1,
    Month == "maj" ~ 1,
    Month == "jun" ~ 1,
    Month == "jul" ~ 1,
    Month == "aug" ~ 1,
    Month == "sep" ~ 2,
    Month == "okt" ~ 2,
    Month == "mar" ~ 3,
  )) %>% 
  mutate(MonthM6 = case_when(
    Month == "apr" ~ 1,
    Month == "maj" ~ 1,
    Month == "jun" ~ 1,
    Month == "jul" ~ 1,
    Month == "aug" ~ 1,
    Month == "sep" ~ 2,
    Month == "okt" ~ 2,
    Month == "mar" ~ 4,
  )) %>% 
  mutate(MonthM7 = case_when(
    Month == "apr" ~ 1,
    Month == "maj" ~ 1,
    Month == "jun" ~ 1,
    Month == "jul" ~ 1,
    Month == "aug" ~ 1,
    Month == "sep" ~ 2,

  )) %>% 
  mutate(MonthM8 = case_when(

    Month == "jun" ~ "P1",
    Month == "jul" ~ "P1",

    Month == "mar" ~ "P3",
  )) %>% 
  mutate(MonthM9 = case_when(
    Month == "apr" ~ "P1",

    Month == "jun" ~ "P1",
    Month == "jul" ~ "P1",
    Month == "aug" ~ "P2",
    Month == "sep" ~ "P2",
    Month == "okt" ~ "P2",
    Month == "mar" ~ "P3",
  )) 
  
testM <- function(mA, mB) {
  mAN <- paste0("MonthM",mA)
  mBN <- paste0("MonthM",mB)
  modA <- eval(substitute(lm(log(Weight) ~ variable*log(Length), dat), list(variable = as.name(mAN))))
  modB <- eval(substitute(lm(log(Weight) ~ variable*log(Length), dat), list(variable = as.name(mBN))))
  # print(summary(modA))
  # print(summary(modB))
  print(anova(modA, modB))

  datP <- expand_grid(Length = 40:max(dat$Length), unique(dat[[mAN]]))
  colnames(datP) = c("Length", mAN)
  resA <- predict(modA, datP, interval='prediction', level=0.95) 
  resA <- exp(resA)
  resA <- resA %>% as_tibble() %>% mutate(Model = paste0("M",mA), ModelP = paste0("M",mA,"-",pull(datP[,2]))) 
  resA <- bind_cols(datP, resA) %>% select(- !! mAN)
  colnames(resA)[(ncol(resA)-4):(ncol(resA)-2)] <- c("Avg", "Lower", "Upper")
  
  datP <- expand_grid(Length = 40:max(dat$Length), unique(dat[[mBN]]))
  colnames(datP) = c("Length", mBN)
  resB <- predict(modB, datP, interval='prediction', level=0.95) 
  resB <- exp(resB)
  resB <- resB %>% as_tibble() %>% mutate(Model = paste0("M",mB), ModelP = paste0("M",mB,"-",pull(datP[,2]))) 
  resB <- bind_cols(datP, resB) %>% select(- !! mBN)
  colnames(resB)[(ncol(resB)-4):(ncol(resB)-2)] <- c("Avg", "Lower", "Upper")

  res <- bind_rows(resA, resB)
  ggplot(res, aes(x = Length, y = Avg)) + 
    geom_line(aes(group = ModelP, color = ModelP, linetype = Model)) 
}

We test the models against each other:
